[1] Situation as of 6 Aug 2007: flood involved?
Date: Mon 6 Aug 2007
Source: BBC News [edited]
<http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/6932602.stm>

Disease experts probe farm flood
--------------------------------
The BBC's science correspondent, Pallab Ghosh, said he understands that
government scientists are looking into whether a flood at Wolford farm --
where the disease was confirmed on Friday [3 Aug 2007] -- might have been
the means by which animals became infected.
He said an investigation of the [lesions] on the mouths of the cows
suggested that they were infected sometime between 18 and 22 July [2007].
Computer modelling suggests that airborne transmission from the Pirbright
site is a possibility -- but unlikely, he said.
The government says no new cases of foot and mouth disease [FMD] have been
reported in the past 24 hours. About 97 cows have been culled on 2
neighbouring farms -- most as a precaution due to "potentially dangerous
contact".
Speaking after a visit to the Regional Disease Control Centre in Reigate,
Surrey, prime minister Gordon Brown said it was a difficult time. But he
added, "I hope in a short period of time we can say we have contained,
controlled, and eradicated this disease."
Asked about farmers' anger that a research site could be the cause of the
outbreak, the prime minister urged people not to pre-judge the outcome of
the investigations currently under way. He said "every possible source" was
being investigated, adding, "I want to be able to ensure people every
effort is being made and people here are working night and day to contain
this disease."
"We've tested in up to 100 different farming establishments. We've been
testing, obviously, pigs, cattle, sheep, and in some cases goats. "It's
very important that all the tests are done and checked, particularly
obviously with blood tests on sheep. That is being carried out by 150 staff."
The National Farmers' Union [NFU] says its members will be "rightly
horrified" if the vaccine centre is to blame -- inspectors hope to have the
results of their inquiry by Tuesday [7 Aug 2007].
Meanwhile the European Commission has formalised a ban on British exports
of meat, milk products, and live animals.
After meeting Mr Brown at Downing Street on Monday [6 Aug 2007], NFU
President, Peter Kendall, said his members were "angry and very, very
concerned" about speculation linking the virus to the Pirbright facilities.
"It cannot be the case that we have a scientific institution that actually
releases disease into the environment, and our members will be quite
rightly horrified," he said.
Merial has suspended vaccine production but says it has "complete
confidence" in its biosecurity measures and to date its investigations have
shown "no breach" in procedures. Protection and surveillance zones covering
farms in the area have been expanded to 10 km (6.2 mi). But there has been
some criticism that footpaths remain open in the area.
Stephen Bowers, who owns a smallholding on the edge of the exclusion zone,
also said bridleways were open and wild deer were freely moving across the
area adding, "The countryside is open and it's open to infection."
The government has imposed a ban on the movement of all livestock in
England, Scotland, and Wales. The EC has endorsed a British ban on
exporting cattle and animal products. Northern Ireland, which has imposed a
ban on all cattle, sheep, and pigs from Britain, has been excluded.
111 000 farms across UK [have been] affected by movement ban. That includes
10m cattle, 23m sheep, and 5m pigs.
A spokesman said the EC was "very happy with the prompt response of the
British authorities." Environment secretary, Hilary Benn, has urged people
to remain vigilant, as the source of the outbreak has not been confirmed.
He said that the facilities at Pirbright were being redeveloped following a
report made in 2002, as a result of the FMD outbreak the previous year,
which had criticisms of the institute.
Last year [2006], the institute expressed concerns about cuts to its
funding in written evidence given to MPs [members of parliament].
--
